Creating an AWS S3 Bucket Using Terraform â€” Complete Step-by-Step Guide

Infrastructure as Code (IaC) simplifies cloud resource management, and Terraform is one of the most powerful tools available for provisioning infrastructure reliably and repeatably.
In this tutorial, youâ€™ll learn how to configure AWS credentials, initialize Terraform, deploy an S3 bucket, inspect the state, and finally clean up resources.

ğŸ§© Step 1: Configure AWS Credentials

Before Terraform can interact with AWS, export your credential environment variables:

export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID="your-access-key"
export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY="your-secret-key"
export AWS_DEFAULT_REGION="eu-north-1"


These allow Terraform to authenticate with AWS securely without exposing secrets in files.

ğŸ§± Step 2: Create Your Terraform Configuration

Create a file (e.g., main.tf) and add the following:

terraform {
  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = ">= 5.0"
    }
  }
}

provider "aws" {
  region = "eu-north-1"
}

# create an S3 bucket
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "SampleAWSTerraform" {
  bucket = "awsterrafrombucket"

  tags = {
    Name        = "Sample Bucket"
    Environment = "Test"
  }
}


This configuration specifies:

AWS provider configuration

Region (eu-north-1)

An S3 bucket with tags

âš™ï¸ Step 3: Initialize Terraform

Before running any Terraform commands, initialize your working directory:

terraform init


This downloads the AWS provider and prepares Terraform to run.

ğŸ” Step 4: Validate the Configuration

Ensure your Terraform code syntax is correct:

terraform validate


If everything is valid, youâ€™ll get:

Success! The configuration is valid.

ğŸ“ Step 5: Generate the Execution Plan

Preview the changes Terraform will apply:

terraform plan


Terraform displays an execution plan showing that 1 resource will be created (your S3 bucket).
This step allows you to confirm the expected changes.

ğŸš€ Step 6: Apply the Changes

Deploy your infrastructure:

terraform apply


Terraform will ask for confirmation:

Do you want to perform these actions?
Enter a value: yes


After typing yes, the S3 bucket will be created.

You should see:

Apply complete! Resources: 1 added, 0 changed, 0 destroyed.

ğŸ“„ Step 7: View the Current State

To inspect the deployed resource:

terraform show


This displays everything Terraform is managing, including the S3 bucket details such as ARN, region, and tags.

ğŸ§¹ Step 8: Destroy the Resources

When you're done and want to clean up:

terraform destroy


Confirm destruction with yes.
Terraform removes all managed resources, ensuring a clean environment.
